1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {The most Caro Kann style
move. Because it's the only one that allows Black to develop his light-squared
bishop that is the main idea of the Caro Kann.} 6. Bg5 {Putting pressure on f6
and threatening to win a pawn on d5. Also this move follows the principle of
maximum activity.} dxc4 7. d5 (7. Bxc4 {Sacrificing the "d" pawn for
development is another alternative, and we are going to check it in another
game.}) 7... Ne5 8. Qd4 {Principle of maximum activity and principle of an
attack!} Nd3+ 9. Bxd3 {Only move.} cxd3 10. Nf3 {Now White doesn't hurry to
recover the pawn: is giving preference to following the opening tasks. Black
has the option of defending the pawn - and we should certainly analyse it.} g6
$6 (10... Bf5 {Developing and defending was an important option.} 11. O-O {
Finishing the opening tasks. Now Black should find a way of developing his
pieces, especially on the king side.} e6 {Is the most natural move, but allows}
(11... Qb6 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qd1 {And White has definite compensation because
Black hasn't developed the king side and the d3 pawn is very weak. Taking the
b2 pawn right now is very risky. And Bf5 is faced with Nh4, recovering the
pawn.}) 12. Qa4+ Qd7 13. Nb5 $18 {With a double threat: Nc7 and Ne5.}) 11. Bxf6
exf6 12. O-O Qb6 (12... Be7 {Is the only move Black has, to survive.} 13. Rfe1
O-O 14. Rad1 {And White's better, because he is going to recover the pawn with
a better position (passed pawn, active pieces).}) 13. Rfe1+ Kd8 14. Qh4 {White
threatening 15.Ne5.} (14. Qxd3 {Was more simple.}) 14... g5 15. Qh5 {White has
a clear advantage. The rest was easy for Botvinik.} Bd6 16. Qxf7 Rf8 17. Qxh7
g4 18. Nd2 Qc7 19. Qh6 Qf7 20. Nc4 Be5 21. Nxe5 fxe5 22. Qg5+ Qe7 23. Qxe5 Qxe5
24. Rxe5 Bf5 25. Rf1 Kd7 26. f3 b5 27. fxg4 Bxg4 28. h3 b4 29. Ne4 Rxf1+ 30.
Kxf1 Rf8+ 31. Ke1 Bf5 32. g4 Bg6 33. Re6 {What you should learn from this game:
1. The importance of development. You may ask: "Just this?" I answer: "YES!
It's very important to know this and to remember it all the time."} 1-0

