1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 Be6 7. a3 $1 {A
excellent move, ignoring for a moment the opening tasks. But White needs to
play this move to support b4 in the future, as you are going to see. I'm going
to explain to you how to discover this move using the following understanding:
"Black's last move demonstrates his intentions of castling queen side, because
with Be6 blocking the "e" pawn, that is the natural move for developing the
king side. That's why White prepares an attack on the queen side with the move
a3".} Qd7 8. Be2 (8. Nf3 {Is the most natural move according to the principle
of the least active piece. But it allows.} Ne4 {And after the exchange.} 9.
Nxe4 dxe4 {Black wins a tempo attacking the f3 knight and is also a pawn up
after} 10. d5 exf3 11. dxe6 Qxe6+ $17) 8... O-O-O 9. c5 {Now White gets queen
side space and you can see how useful the move a3 is going to be in this
position.} Ne4 10. Nf3 {Developing.} Nxg5 11. Nxg5 h6 12. Nf3 g5 {Black should
attack on the king side and develop his pieces, but White's attack comes first.
} 13. b4 g4 14. b5 $1 {An excellent intermediate move.} gxf3 15. bxc6 Qxc6 16.
Bxf3 {White has the advantage and the plan is to push the "c" pawn in some way.
Look how GM Adams treats the rest of the game, in a very simple way.} Bf5 17.
O-O Rg8 18. Re1 e6 19. Rc1 h5 20. Na2 $1 {Logical move according to the plan.}
h4 21. Rc3 f6 22. Nb4 Qb5 23. Be2 {Forcing Black's queen to adopt a passive
situation.} Qe8 24. c6 $1 Bxb4 25. axb4 Be4 26. f3 Bf5 27. Qa4 Bh3 28. Qxa7
Rxg2+ 29. Kh1 {What you should learn about this game: 1. The reason for the
move a3.. 2. How to think about your plan depending on your opponent's last
move (Be6) 3. Manoeuvre 20. Na2-b4 to help the move c6.} 1-0

