1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 dxc4 7. Bxc4 Qxd4 {
Now Black captures the pawn but White gets a lot of development in
compensation.} 8. Qxd4 Nxd4 9. O-O-O {Developing and attacking that is always
ideal in the opening.} e5 10. f4 {White wants to open the position.} Bg4 11.
Nf3 {Sacrificing another pawn to get more development and open even more the
position.} Nxf3 12. gxf3 Bxf3 13. fxe5 {Look at White's situation - very
comfortable and with a lot of compensation.} Bxh1 {The best move for Black.
The other options give White a clear advantage.} (13... Nd7 14. Rhf1 $16) 14.
exf6 Rc8 (14... h6 {Is another option.}) 15. Re1+ Kd7 16. Rd1+ $1 {To prevent
Black from castling.} Bd6 {Now White has a great advantage.} (16... Ke8 {Was
better.} 17. Bd3 {With a great position for White.}) 17. Be2 (17. fxg7 {Was
better. In this kind of situation, it is difficult to explain, based on
strategic concepts, which move is better: you need to calculate the specific
variations.} Rhg8 18. Bd3 Bd5 19. Bh6 $16) 17... gxf6 18. Bxf6 Bg2 19. Be5 {
Now the endgame is better for White. The rest doesn't deserve commentary.} Ke6
20. Bxd6 Rhd8 21. Bg3 Rxd1+ 22. Kxd1 a6 23. Kd2 Kf5 24. Bd3+ Kg4 25. Nd1 Kg5
26. Bxh7 Rf8 27. Bd3 f5 28. h4+ Kh5 29. Be2+ Kg6 30. Bf4 Be4 31. Nc3 Bc6 32. a3
Re8 33. h5+ Kf6 34. h6 Kg6 35. Bd3 Re7 36. Bc2 Bf3 37. Bd3 Re8 38. Bc4 Bc6 39.
Be2 Re7 40. Bd3 Re8 41. a4 Rd8 42. Ke3 Re8+ 43. Kd2 Rd8 44. Ke3 Re8+ 45. Kf2
Rd8 46. Bc2 Re8 47. Be3 Re7 48. Ne2 Be4 49. Bb3 Re8 50. Nd4 Kh7 51. Bf4 Rc8 52.
Nf3 Bb1 53. Ne5 Rd8 54. Bf7 Rd6 55. Be8 {What you should learn about this game:
1. The playing style in this variation. 2. The subtle idea Re1+ followed by
Rd1+, preventing Black from castling.} 1-0

