1. c4 {Another move in order to reach a Panov position.} c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5
cxd5 4. d4 {The Panov was reached.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 dxc4 7. Bxc4 {
Sacrificing the pawn for development} e6 {Black doesn't take the pawn. We will
analyse this in another game.} 8. Nf3 {Developing and maximum activity.} Be7 9.
O-O O-O 10. Rc1 {White has a more active position.} a6 11. Bd3 {This is the
typical position for this bishop in Isolated "d" pawn positions. Because
White's plan is to attack on the king side and this square is the best for the
purpose of attacking h7.} Bd7 {Black's finishing his development.} 12. Re1 {
Maximum activity.} Rc8 13. h4 {Typical move. At some point, Black should play
g6. So White prepares to play h5 against g6. Also provides the h2 square for
the king. But maybe this move isn't the most accurate, as it isn't really
necessary to play it right now. Maybe something like 13. Ne5, following the
principle of maximum activity, was better.} Nb4 14. Bb1 {In this kind of
position, this bishop is a very important piece for three reasons: 1. First of
all, White should avoid exchanges because all the endings favour Black. 2.
Controls a lot of important squares (c4,d5,e4). 3. Helps White attack the king
side.} Bc6 15. Ne5 {Following the principle of maximum activity.} g6 16. Qb3 {
Developing the queen and attacking the b4 knight. This move sacrifices the d4
pawn and Black didn't capture it.} Nbd5 (16... Qxd4 $5 17. Rcd1 Qc5 18. Nxc6
Nxc6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Ne4 Qe5 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Qxb7 $13) 17. Nxc6 {A
typical move. Now Black is going to have a weak pawn on the c6 square.} bxc6
18. Na4 {Going to the c5 square.} Nd7 19. Qg3 Bxg5 20. hxg5 Qa5 21. b3 Rfd8 22.
Be4 Qd2 23. Red1 Qb4 24. Bxd5 $1 {Great understanding by GM Ivanchuk. White
has the advantage now! The rest is instructive but doesn't deserve commentary
because it's out of our subject.} cxd5 25. Rc7 Rxc7 26. Qxc7 Qb8 27. Rc1 Qa8
28. Rc6 Nf8 29. Nc5 e5 30. Rf6 exd4 31. Qxf7+ Kh8 32. Rxa6 Qb8 33. Ra7 Qe5 34.
Nd3 {What you should learn from this game: 1. The importance of the
light-squared bishop in the Isolated "d" pawn positions. 2. The strategic idea
of the move 17.Nxc6.3. A little bit about how to play positions with an
isolated "d" pawn.} 1-0

