1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 {White should
wait until Black has played e6 before playing c5. Now we get the pawn
structure that we already learned how to play in the 5...e6 variation.} 7. c5
h6 8. Bxf6 (8. Bf4 {Putting the bishop in this "super square" was another
interesting alternative. You already know the power of the bishop placed here.}
) 8... Qxf6 9. Bb5 {The typical square for the bishop here, indirectly
controlling the e5 square.} g6 10. Nf3 Bg7 11. Qd2 Bd7 12. Rd1 {Providing the
d4 pawn with super protection.} O-O 13. O-O {White simply develops his pieces
and has the typical advantage of this pawn structure.} Qd8 14. Rfe1 b6 15. Bxc6
Bxc6 16. b4 {Getting the protected passed pawn.} bxc5 17. bxc5 Rb8 18. Ne5 Be8
19. f4 {White has a clear advantage here. The rest was easy for GM Ehlvest,
because Black's bishop pair is inferior to White's knights and the "c" pawn
gives White a strategic advantage. Also Black has nothing to do.} f6 20. Nd3
Bf7 21. Rb1 g5 22. Rxb8 Qxb8 23. Rb1 Qc8 24. Nb5 Bg6 25. Nd6 Qa6 26. Nb4 Qa5
27. f5 exf5 28. Rb2 Rd8 29. Nb7 {What you should learn about this game: 1.
It's mainly to review the things that we learnt in the 5...e6 variation. 2.
You must remember to play c5 if Black plays e6 with the light-squared bishop
inside the pawn chain e6-d5.} 1-0

